You'll declare four spades. Before you play a card, count your winners outside diamonds: six trump tricks, the \H A, and a club give you ten — the contract is already there. That means you can afford to handle diamonds with total safety.
[ROLE leader][STAGE auction-end]
They roared to four spades, so declarer holds the cards. Your singleton diamond king is a lonely honor — there's nothing to guard it if the ace comes down.
[ROLE defender][STAGE auction-end]
Declarer is in four spades after a strong sequence. Your long hearts headed by the \H KQ are the defense's one real engine — but only if you can win a trick to cash them.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead a heart, your partner's likely suit and the safe choice. Whatever you do, don't lead your singleton diamond king into declarer's \D AQ — that just hands him the suit.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
This is the whole point of the deal. In diamonds you have \D AQ and small opposite three small, missing the king. The finesse — low to the queen — loses to West's king, and East is the danger hand: once on lead, East cashes long hearts and you're down. But you don't need a diamond trick at all. Cash the \D A: West's king is singleton, so it falls, and you never give up the lead. That's Rabbi's Rule — when the king is singleton offside, play the ace.
[ROLE defender][STAGE post-lead]
You sit with the long hearts behind dummy, and they'd beat the contract — if you ever get in. A careful declarer keeps you off lead by dropping the bare diamond king under the ace, so guard your hearts and hope.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
You counted ten tricks before diamonds, so cashing the \D A — never the finesse — was the safe play, and West's stiff king came down. The queen scored an extra trick on top. Eleven tricks — very nicely done.
[ROLE leader][STAGE post-play]
